backup <- read_csv("df.csv")

# Define data type
backup %>%
  mutate(
    user_id = as.factor(user_id),
    tweet_id = as.factor(tweet_id),
    friend_id = as.factor(account_id)
  ) %>%
  dplyr::select(-account_id) -> backup

# Making new variables
# (1) Maximum number of each user's friends: max_friends_count 
# What is the maximum of user_friends_count? 
backup %>% 
  dplyr::select(user_id, user_friends_count) %>% 
  distinct() %>% 
  group_by(user_id) %>% 
  mutate(max_friends_count = max(user_friends_count)) %>% 
  dplyr::select(-user_friends_count) %>% 
  distinct() -> max_data
# max_data: a new dataframe with `user_id` and `max_friends_count` as variables  

# Merge this 'max_data' into backup 
backup %>% 
  merge(max_data, by="user_id") -> backup

# (2) Timestamp data of each tweet: tweet_timestamp 
# Let's clean timestamp data to have affinity with R lubridate pacakge 

list_timestamp <- str_split(backup$tweet_timestamp, " ")  # make a list containing each string component of timestamp data 

Month = c()  # make an empty vector 
Day = c() 
Time = c()
Year = c() 
timestamp_dmyt = c() 

# fill these vectors with month, day, time, year components within each list element
for (i in 1:length(list_timestamp)) {
  list_timestamp[[i]][2] -> Month[i] 
  list_timestamp[[i]][3] -> Day[i]
  list_timestamp[[i]][4] -> Time[i]
  list_timestamp[[i]][6] -> Year[i]
  }

timestamp_dmyt = as.data.frame(cbind(Day, Month, Year, Time)) # bind these filled vectors and make it as a dataframe; store this dataframe as 'timestamp_dmyt' 

# now paste the strings into one and store them in a vector 'dmyt' 
dmyt = c() 
for (i in 1:nrow(timestamp_dmyt)) {
  dmyt[i] = paste(Day[i], Month[i], Year[i], Time[i])
}

# make 'dmyt' vector as a new variable of dataframe: 'tweet_timestamp'
backup$tweet_timestamp = dmy_hms(dmyt)  # timestamp format: day-month-year-hour-minute-second 

# (3) Define x-axis: number of tweets collected
backup %>%
  arrange(tweet_timestamp) %>%  # arrange the data by time
  mutate(old_x = cumsum(!duplicated(tweet_id))) -> backup

Ro’ee: Do low-quality sources tweet more frequently? If this is the case, we would need smaller number of tweets to reach the plateau (estimated in pilot data: 800 tweets for 67% of distinct friends seen).

➔ Low quality vs. others - do they have different frequencies of posting?

  • x: low quality = yes (28) or no (the rest)

    • low_quality would be our x variable (x)

  • y: frequencies of posting

    • the max # of tweets that each friend_id has produced over the data collection period (max_n_tweets)
backup_lowq %>% 
  group_by(friend_id) %>%
  mutate(cumulativesum = cumsum(!duplicated(tweet_id))) %>%  
  summarize(max_n_tweets = max(cumulativesum)) -> max_no_tweets

backup_lowq |> 
  left_join(max_no_tweets, by="friend_id") -> backup_lowq

backup_lowq |> 
  group_by(friend_id) |> 
  summarise(timediff = max(tweet_timestamp) - min(tweet_timestamp)) -> timeDiff2

backup_lowq |> 
  merge(timeDiff2, by="friend_id") |>
  group_by(friend_id) |>
  mutate(
    avg_n_tweets_perhour = (max_n_tweets / as.numeric(timediff))*60*60
  ) |> 
  ungroup() -> lowq_vs_others


lowq_vs_others |>
  mutate(
    x = ifelse(is.na(low_quality), "no", low_quality)
  ) %>% 
  dplyr::select(screen_name,max_n_tweets, avg_n_tweets_perhour, x) %>% 
  unique() ->  lowq_vs_others

Do low quality accounts post more frequently on average than other accounts? ➔ t-test

t.test(max_n_tweets ~ x, data = lowq_vs_others) -> model1

nice_table((stats.table <- tidy(model1, conf.int = TRUE)), broom = "t.test", note="Group 1: Others ; Group 2: Low Quality", title="Is there a statistically significant difference in the maximum number of tweets produced between low-quality accounts and other accounts?")

Conclusion

  • Among all 60 users, 85% (90%) of users who follow low-quality accounts are revealed up to around 33K (48K) of tweets
plot_a2 + geom_vline(xintercept=33000, lty=2, color="orange") + geom_hline(yintercept=0.85, lty=2, color="orange") + geom_hline(yintercept=0.9, lty=4, color="skyblue") + geom_vline(xintercept=48000, lty=4, color="skyblue")

  • Low quality accounts produce more tweets compared to other accounts on average (max # of tweets).
